Summary: k8s executor failed to start on java 25 due to kerberos gss init error
Status: Open

k8s executor failed to start on java 25 due to kerberos init error, the log like:
[dispatcher-CoarseGrainedScheduler] ERROR TaskSchedulerImpl: Lost an executor 2 (already removed): Unable to create executor due to Failed on local exception: 
java.io.IOException: javax.security.sasl.SaslException: GSS initiate failed [Caused by GSSException: No valid credentials provided (Mechanism level: Failed to find any Kerberos tgt)]; Host Details : local host is: "sparksql-197af89cb7bae1bd-exec-
2/10.15."; destination host is: "10.147.":56310; 
h3. Root Cause

In jdk 22+ ([https://openjdk.org/jeps/486] ), *Subject.doAs()* uses _ScopedValue_ instead of {_}InheritableThreadLocal{_}. New threads no longer inherit the caller's Subject.

executor calls *SparkHadoopUtil.runAsSparkUser()* → *UGI.doAs(sparkUser)* to establish a security context. In the old JDK, child task threads inherited the sparkUser Subject via {_}InheritableThreadLocal{_}, so *UGI.getCurrentUser()* returned *sparkUser* with delegation tokens.

But on JDK 25, child threads cannot see the sparkUser Subject, so that *UGI.getCurrentUser()* falls back to {*}UGI.getLoginUser(){*}( [https://github.com/apache/hadoop/blob/master/hadoop-common-project/hadoop-common/src/main/java/org/apache/hadoop/security/UserGroupInformation.java#L586-L594|https://github.com/apache/hadoop/blob/8ac9721a1d741c1a1bc010c23280ad233ba0ee43/hadoop-common-project/hadoop-common/src/main/java/org/apache/hadoop/security/UserGroupInformation.java#L586-L594] ), which was initialized during JAAS login without any delegation tokens. The first outbound RPC from a child thread triggers SASL negotiation, fails to find a matching token, attempts kerberos GSSAPI, and fails because there is no TGT either. the executor will never be started and registered.

This issue is specific to Spark on k8s, not affect on yarn. On Yarn, the *{{HADOOP_TOKEN_FILE_LOCATION}}* environment variable serves as a built-in safety fallback.
h3. Proposed Workaround (For Discussion)

LoginUser is held in a class-level static field, not a thread-local. Add delegation tokens to loginUser in {*}SparkHadoopUtil.addDelegationTokens(){*}, so that child threads falling back to loginUser can still find the tokens:

[https://github.com/apache/spark/blob/master/core/src/main/scala/org/apache/spark/deploy/SparkHadoopUtil.scala#L156-L162|https://github.com/apache/spark/blob/da66413fdf7ad44c0cfb58457b80856745eadc13/core/src/main/scala/org/apache/spark/deploy/SparkHadoopUtil.scala#L156-L162] 

 
{code:java}
private[spark] def addDelegationTokens(tokens: Array[Byte], sparkConf: SparkConf): Unit = {
  UserGroupInformation.setConfiguration(newConfiguration(sparkConf))
  val creds = deserialize(tokens)
  addCurrentUserCredentials(creds)
  // JDK 25+: Subject.callAs() uses ScopedValue, child threads do not inherit
  // currentUser's Subject and fall back to loginUser. Add DTs to loginUser so
  // that child threads can still authenticate.
  val loginUser = UserGroupInformation.getLoginUser
  if (loginUser != null && loginUser != UserGroupInformation.getCurrentUser) {
    loginUser.addCredentials(creds)
  }
} {code}
The fix should be safe because addCredentials is additive.  Although, Hadoop 3.5.0 addresses this by HADOOP-19574 HADOOP-19670, the fix may be still needed because many spark deployments older than 3.5.0.

I am proposing this purely as a temporary workaround. I would love to hear your thoughts on this approach and discuss any potential risks or better alternatives.

